title: Do musicians see the Beatles as average at playing music? - Quora

response.answer_text: I decided to learn how to play guitar after hearing “Song of the Wind” on Santana’s album “Caravanserai”. As I kept progressing on the guitar I got enamoured by John McLaughlin’s playing and spent years focusing on how to reach that level of guitar prowess. To cut the long story short, I eventually managed to learn how to play guitar solos real fast, how to utilize complicated arpeggios, scales, patterns etc. That practice led me to the point where I was able to figure out and copy many different styles and idioms (my last foray into tackling guitar styles was with the French Manouche Gypsy playing a la Django Reinhardt). But I still, to this day and despite accumulating so much experience in various styles, cannot figure out how did the Beatles come up with and how did they play their music. The Beatles are the biggest mystery of all, to me. I spent many hours trying to cop George’s intros, licks, solos, only to fail miserably. I also spent many hours trying to figure out Paul’s bass lines — to no avail. I spend many hours trying to imitate Lennon’s rhythm parts — couldn’t do it. So it speaks volumes, I think, to say that after being able to copy and play convincingly John McLaughlin guitar lines, I fail miserably trying to do the same with many Beatles guitar lines. To me, anyone who claims that the Beatles were not musical virtuosos is not really listening close enough. Yes, almost anyone can mimic their music, and if you’re not listening closely you may think they nailed it, but that’s never the case. You can watch many Beatles cover bands on youtube, many musicians explaning how to play Beatles guitar parts, but they’re all way off. It’s those last 5% - 10% of the subtle details in phrasing that no one seems capable of figuring out. Not to mention the stupendous genius of being able to come up with such ideas in the first place.

Musician-bashing is a popular pastime and The Beatles are an easy target. Critics at the time certainly felt they had no talent or promise. In my view the joy of rock, pop music is its closeness to home. The feeling of "Hey they're just like us, I bet I could do that" skiffle ethic is what created The Beatles and many similar bands. If you really examine it virtually no popular bands (or composers, as a stereotype) have flawless-sounding performances on their records. This is a relatively rare feature. Usually performance technique gets honed down with tons of touring, which the Beatles had gotten tired of by the time they really started creatively flourishing in the studio, or from intense study (think Robert Johnson who was once so talentless people thought he had made a deal with the devil). As a crude stereotype there are pop musicians and musician's musicians: the former sells lots of records, the latter generally does not. There's a clear trade-off here and sometimes it's frankly not worth it, if you can sell just as many records and without having to practice yourself crazy. If the Beatles had tried to be a musician's musician virtuoso band, they wouldn't have had as much of an audience and they would've lost much of their creative vibrancy, seeing as this was at odds with their character, aptitude. And it's a good thing The Beatles didn't have flawless performances or no one would cover their songs and they would make that much less in royalties. It's often been said The Beatles can't sing. Well compared to who? When I think of highly acclaimed rock singers I think of guys like Layne Staley, Chris Cornell, Robert Plant, Jeff Buckley… But if you listen to their interviews and early material it's clear they still have a long way to go. As Robert Plant puts it "I'm not a 'real' singer….I'm just up there doing my thing". Robert Plant on Jeff Buckley. He also had harsh words about Stairway to Heaven. Hating Your Golden Goose John Lennon was critical of much of The Beatles' catalogue. Musicians are already their own biggest critics without people at home loudly critiquing everything they've ever done as well. Almost every rock and pop band has warts that are low-hanging fruit. Jimmy Page liked shredding not in time, Hendrix wrote some lazy songs, Beethoven is overrated, Miles Davis can't play trumpet, John Coltrane/Mozart/whoever plays way too many notes, Dave Grohl isn't that good of a drummer, experimental bands like Radiohead/Yes/Pink Floyd write bad lyrics or can't sing, Elvis shook hands with Nixon and died on the toilet, Michelangelo paints manly women, Mona Lisa doesn't have any eyebrows…. Fighting words, all of them. There's a touch of truth there but who cares. Marvel at what they ARE shooting for and getting right, how their music makes you feel etc, what it does, not all the many and irrelevant ways it falls short here and there of some impossible ideal. In terms of execution there IS such a thing as "good enough". The Beatles' stuff generally falls in this bucket for me. This question is more or less an accurate take of their technical vocabulary, but misses the broader question of their talents, innovations, accomplishments, and work ethic.

This question misses the mark somewhat. It’s not like the Beatles were virtuoso players. John Lennon was not a very nimble guitar player, compared to, say, Eric Clapton. Ringo Starr was not as fast and furious as Keith Moon. The Beatles could not play fluent and responsive jams that others could enjoy, in the manner of the Allman Brothers Band. That doesn’t matter. What matters is that the Beatles had much greater musical imagination than most bands. The songs they came up with were exceptionally memorable and inventive and stylistically very diverse, and they were capable enough musicians to play them with taste and conviction. They seldom tried to play anything that they just couldn’t do. I personally think that they overreached themselves on ‘Helter Skelter’, aiming for a level of chaotic fury that wasn’t suited to them at all, but loads of their fans disagree with me. The proof of the pudding is their recordings: do they contain any instances where the band failed to do justice to the material? Some, but very few. In general they played their music as well as anyone has played it, and they did more than justice to the songs they covered. Not that anybody could have redeemed the chintz-fest that is ‘Mr. Moonlight’. For what it’s worth, anyone who saw them live before the audience was so loud that it drowned the band out, says that they were a very, very good rock & roll band indeed: Lemmy from Motorhead always swore that they were the most powerful band he ever saw. It was the energy and skill of their live performances that got them noticed in the first place. Later, when they couldn’t hear themselves, they played less well.

Not one member of The Beatles was the best at their instrument. Actually, not one was even in the top ten with the possible exception of Paul on bass. But that turned out not to matter. What made them great were other things centering on songs. They were constantly pushing what was considered possible in the world of pop/rock song construction. While most songs produced in the ’60s had two to four chords The Beatles would release songs with 16 different chords. “I Am the Walrus” has eight in the first minute*. You can’t evaluate the lads from Liverpool based on how well they could jam. They weren’t the kind of musicians that could dazzle you with solos. Cream could do that. The Jimi Hendrix Experience could do that. But that’s just not what The Beatles were about. They dazzled you with their shear audacity, their depth of imagination and their ability to take diverse musical styles and bend them to their will. No one approached them in this regard then, and few have come close to them since. They broke ground no one even knew was there. That is what makes them not only above average, but truly great. *Thank you Howard Goodall.

I played music professionally for nearly 10 years. I was friends with tons of musicians. And musicians talk about music. The general consensus was that as players, they weren’t incredibly gifted. Virtuosity is quite overrated. If you don’t believe me, try to listen to Dream Theater. They are amazing players,but to no real purpose except for playing well. I’ll take a Motown cut any day over music that is overplayed and overshoots the mark - the song. It’s all about the song. (Who influenced more music: Motown or Dream Theater?) :::::: See Edit ::::: Paul was probably the most musically gifted, and besides his great voice and his own songwriting skills, he took the bass into new and interesting places. George wasn’t as good as Clapton or Hendrix, but it wasn’t necessary. He was clever and had many sly and understated parts. Anyone who says Ringo was awful should look at YouTube and see some of today’s great drummers sing his praises. Ringo could lay a groove in a unique way, and he didn’t need to be flashy. If he was too flashy he’d be in the way of Paul’s work. A lot of times you’ll hear musicians quote (some famous jazz musician; it’s attributed to lots of people) that after you learn to play, you learn what NOT to play. Ringo was right where he needed to be. Every beat was for the benefit of the song. Which brings me to John. Capable guitar work, flashes of genius, but when he wrote a song, especially one that meant something to him (and John was always trying to work out what was in his head, finding out who he was, whereas Macca was an entertainer who could switch genres at the drop of a hat, and thus seemed less authentic-sorry, Paul), John was peerless. And those 4 guys always, always played with the song in mind, played what served the song best. BTW, Helter Skelter is a masterpiece *because* it feels like it it could fall to pieces at any second, but it doesn’t. It’s straight up, ballsy proto-metal. So, I would venture to say that they were phenomenal. :::: Edit 9/27/19 I am just going to take a moment to say that I have no intention to throw as much shade on Dream Theater as it appears that I have. I, as many of us have done, tend to forget that sometimes an offhand example can sound - especially when said online - like either a sweeping categorization or an attempt to make an irrefutable truth, and I had no intention of doing that. I was looking for an example of overplaying, and I have had a particularly bad experience with a terrible sound engineer who worshipped them, so they popped to mind. They (DT) are just guys doing what a lot of us would like to still be doing, and are not demons or the bane of all music. Also, I probably should have clarified (and anyone who knows me would testify to the fact) that I do indeed think that The Beatles were definitely incredibly gifted. I was thinking, when I wrote this, about “gifted” in terms of technical musicianship, such as that of Coltrane. ::::

response.answer_text: Do musicians see the Beatles as average at playing music? Playing music - certainly better than average - because your average person can’t play at all. Better than a professional musician, possibly. But the Beatles were greater than the sum of their parts. They didn’t have huge voice range, but not everyone can be Roy Orbison. Their harmonies were very good, and their musical innovation is what made them so special. My favorite example of this is how Paul McCartney went to a symphony performance of the Brandenburg Concerto then chose to use a piccolo trumpet in Penny Lane. New. Innovative. Entertaining. Now the Beatles didn’t play in the era of Autotune, and their live performances were charged with emotion, but older people in that era thought that rock music - specifically the electric guitar sound and its inherent dissonant overtones - was categorically bad. It wasn’t bad - it was different. One of my favorite things about Beatles music, is that it transcends its genre. Take one of the better, more lyrical Beatles songs like “Let it Be”, and hear it performed by a symphony orchestra. I challenge any music fan to tell me it’s bad. No complaining about shaggy haircuts, shrieking voices, dissonant electric guitars. Just the melody that catches your attention and settles in your ear. Playing wasn’t their strength - but their music will endure because of its total package.

I don’t, and I am a musician. Here is some very tangible proof, for me at least. Watch the iconic Ed Sullivan performances (available on blu ray, and SO worth it!) Paul is not just singing pitch perfect, he is playing perfect and complex baselines all the while. AND… while doing both… he is mugging for the cameras. It’s just amazing to watch in detail. You’d be amazed how well the Blu Ray restoration is after just seeing it grainy for the last 50 years. more proof? listen to the BBC sessions. When they play the songs you know, they sound perfect. Not even live… just studio perfect. I guess that is that 10,000 Gladwellian hours at play. the Beatles are NOT overrated, as much as it is cool to say.

One of my most memorable experiences as a guitarist and vocalist was a few years ago as a member of a classic rock cover band. We had a few Beatles tunes under our belt when we landed a gig playing for a couple of busloads of out-of-towners who paid for transportation, dinner, entertainment and Paul McCartney concert tickets at MSG. We proceeded to add to our set the (almost) complete side of Abbey Road from “You Never Give Me Your Money” non-stop to “The End”. Learning the chords, licks, song changes and harmonies was truly fulfilling. None of the music was particularly difficult to play but it was like learning a symphony. Beautiful melodies, tasteful lead licks, interesting rhythm changes, great lyrics and wonderful harmonies. Individually the Beatles were very good musicians, but not great. But they were great song writers and inventive musical artists. Together they were much more that the sum of their parts. A perfect musical storm.

Sure, and many other musicians where average as well. The list is too long to write, so I won’t bother writing it out. What you can’t take away from them is that every note, drum hit, and vocal did exactly one thing, and it did that one thing very well: it served the music. Like anyone, musicians have their opinion on this matter. For some, shredding at 200BPM is the hallmark of musicianship. For others, it’s just about making good and pleasing music, offering an escape from the day-to-day. I’m squarely in the latter camp. Ask a drummer what he or she thinks of Ringo, and he’s universally lauded as an excellent drummer, often making Top X lists. He may have been average, but once again, no more and no less than what was needed for the Beetles. Like any band, no musician is the entire picture. Even soloists can’t build a band without bringing on other musicians. The whole is stronger than the parts, and maybe the whole of the Beetles was larger than we’d expect.

I am going to say that I, as a professional musician, see them as very good craftsmen versus outright virtuosos. They are certainly better than 90% of all bands in their understanding and execution of rock elements, plus their native genius in deciding on elements that display imagination and alternation of standard musical cliches, such as novel drumming patterns, chords that buck the normal imagination, interest in electronic, foreign and alternate sources of sound production. Later on in their recording history it was the ‘collage’ of sounds that became more important than what they could actually play live. So they became ‘Auteurs’ rather than just performers. But as far as playing goes they ain't no Eric Claptons/Jimi Hendrixes/Gene Krupas. Rather, they kept the focus in terms of real, human, dramatic elements instead of focusing on special effects (analogous to how many modern, movies are overproduced in the special effects department). My two cents.

I’m a veteran of many bands of various genres. Assuming one has the basics mastered, The Beatles taught the world that the ONLY CONSIDERATION is creativity and taste. Virtuosity is not necessary if one is a talented creative like each of The Beatles were. Yes, in terms of technique, The Beatles were “average.” But in terms of what I’d term true talent, wit, originality, and excellent taste, they were phenomenal. Anyone judging The Beatles ONLY in terms of technique is missing a far greater reality. Their vocals and harmony were excellent and trend-setting. They fairly defined that thing called “style.” Instrumentally, they played TOGETHER, with imagination, and great variety. Lennon/McCartney: creative geniuses. Starr/Harrison: perfect team players. The Beatles: The Best.

I'm a big Beatles fan, but even I am willing to admit that once they got the airship off the ground, everything they did was placed in the stratosphere of hype. Mediocre tracks became top five hits. Good tracks became number ones etc. So I'm not going to get on the Hindenburg with everybody else and say they were virtuoso performers in spite of not being virtuoso performers. Listening to them play, Ringo's drumming is quite nifty. Paul's baselines stand out for their cleveress. Whatever John is doing blends in well because it is not noticeable. George's leads are passable at times, at other times they are embarrassing, even by 60s standards. I hate to poke a hole in the airship, but let's get our feet on the ground folks. The Fab Four were fabulous at songwriting.The Fab Four were fabulous at singing tight two and three part harmony.What they were unFab at was their instruments, but they were good enough that they didn't need a backup band or studio musicians.

Calling the Beatles average at playing music is like calling Bob Dylan average at singing. It totally misses the point. The Beatles set the standard for rock songwriting (Dylan did that for folk songwriting,) studio production, and what it means to form a rock band. Without them, Hendrix, Clapton, and Jimmy Page would have been just cooler versions of Les Paul, and the Van Halen brothers would be running a conservatory. Yes, Chuck Berry, Elvis, and Buddy Holly came first, but the Beatles defined the idea of a rock band.

Art, including music, is not served by grading it hierarchically. You don’t get allocated points based on different sets of skills and knowledge. You don’t get medals for getting to the end of a song quicker than others do. The Beatles were not asked to play Bach or Ellington and judge how well they did it for a music exam. They loved rock’n’roll and other kinds of music, and they wanted to play it. They did that in their own way. They were overnight sensations only after years of rehearsal and performances, honing their skills to play what they wanted to play in the way they wanted to play it . Including covers. That is, with each step of their career, they achieved what they set out to achieve. And it was both popular and at the cutting edge. That is not what “average” does. And when they were losing a cohesive sight of what they wanted to achieve as a group, they split up. They may not have had the most refined tools in the toolshed, but they knew how to use what they had extremely creatively and effectively.

Depends on the musician. There is a school of thought among guitar players, specifically, that values soloing, speedy picking, double tapping, etc. Think Eddie Van Halen or Steve Vai. No one doubts that those guys are exemplary musicians. However, the Beatles played a variety of instruments. They also composed some really memorable music, and used harmonically complex chord and melody structures for a lot of their music. When they played together early in their career, in Hamburg, Germany, they played multiple shows a day EVERY DAY for months. They became an incredibly tight band after this experience. As musicians/composers, I would say they are gifted and accomplished.

If you want instrumental virtuosity, then listen to a genre where virtuosity is a key part of the aesthetic. Classical music or jazz. Classical Indian sitar music. The Beatles were in the business of creating pop/rock music. They were singer/songwriters. In these genres, instrumental virtuosity is rarely the point. After all, the instrumentalists in these genres are all merely vocal accompanists. This is a key understanding: in pop/rock it’s all about the vocal and the song. The accompanying instruments are there merely in supporting roles. So, there’s little point in virtuosic performance. Even famous rock players like Clapton or Hendrix can’t hold a candle to great classical or jazz virtuosos. On the other hand, the Beatles were VERY good at creating clever or interesting instrumental parts that supported the vocals. Consider Paul’s baseline on Help from my Friends or George’s harmonized 12 string part on And Your Bird Can Sing. Clever, original, supportive - but not difficult or virtuosic. Nor should they be! That would be beside the point, and would just get in the way. Hope this helps!

In terms of pure instrumental ability, and overall musical knowledge I don’t think any of The Beatles would claim to be absolutely ‘top notch’, this is not what their music, or the musical culture of the times valued. Distinctive expression, creative scope, unique adaptation, quirky angles, solid grooves, energy, action, remarkable communication, dynamic presentations, Ironic declarations, humor - all of these adjectives and descriptive terms apply to The Beatles, they were not on the road to musical perfection. Other bands from their times were way more musically gifted, ‘Cream’ is a good example, Cream were all about the music, the skill, the creative energy. Pink Floyd, I think were definitely more musically endowed than any of the Beatles. However, the abilities and talents of the 4 guys of The Beatles were sufficient, and well enough developed to enable them to produce the kind of music which they intended to convey, their musical ability was enough, it was up to the task! As a musician myself, I can recognize the territory The Beatles inhabited musically speaking, their abilities developed and improved with the help and direction of their mentor and great friend, George Martin. I think in terms of sheer musical input, George Martin deserves much more credit than he actually got for the success of The Beatles, they certainly possessed the raw, creative energy, but he enabled them to become truly great.

Check out the number of Beatle tribute bands that can play Beatles songs Note for note Check out how many videos exist for learning to play: “ guitar parts just like George” “… Like john” “…bass just like Paul” “… Secrets to Ringos drum patterns” The thing is, John, Paul, George, Ringo all DID IT FIRST! Their ear for putting together incredible mixes of newly created music parts is what made them special, not an untouchable virtuosity

Not at all. They were all very good players. And Paul’s bass playing was exceptional. But Paul and John were songwriters first (George grew into a songwriter also.) And they all played to serve the song. Not to show off. Their playing was perfect for their songs. And their songs were perfect for the times. And that makes them exceptional musicians.

They were pretty good players. All 4 of them were a little quirky on their respective instruments; they just went at things a little differently. And compared to some of the real whiz-bang players of the day, the Claptons and Hendrixes of the world, their playing wasn’t anything special at all. However, it didn’t matter. Their songwriting was so much better than everyone—EVERYONE—else’s that the technical proficiency didn’t matter so much. It’s almost universally agreed upon that Beatles music was the best, and absolutely the most popular, music of their era. It was their songwriting, along with the energy that only they could provide, that made this so. They were good enough players to do a fine job of playing Beatles music, which was the toppermost of the poppermost. It still hasn’t been touched.

I was 3 1/2 years old when The Beatles first came to America, but I never really become aware of their music until I was about ten. That’s when I got my first transistor radio, and I was able to listen to whatever music I wanted to. Back in those days, there was no way of knowing who the artist of any particular song was unless the DJ happened to mention it. I always liked The Beatles, but their music was only a small part of the soundtrack of my life. I didn’t fully appreciate them until I was well into my adult years. And now, with so much information on the Internet, my appreciation for The Beatles continues to grow. Take the song, “Here Comes The Sun” for example. Even though I have been playing acoustic guitar for 43 years, I never bothered to learn how to play that song. I came across a video of a guy last week, who broke it down and showed you how to play it. So, I sat down with my guitar and followed along. It was surprisingly easy, and yet the progression is remarkably elegant—even brilliant. It’s also a lot of fun to play.

Certainly depends on the musicians. Those who pride themselves as virtuosos might. However, the members of the Beatles had tremendous that went well beyond simply playing fast. More than any other band. perhaps, the Beatles managed to be both highly sophisticated and capable of making music that was to become popular to a large group of people. Could they have made a living as session players? McCartney certainly could have. George, likely, as well. But that doesn’t matter, because they were too good at songwriting and creating music, to worry about things like that.

Paul is a great song writer and wrote some brilliant bass lines. George had some great riffs. None required any extra talent. So it's hard to say if they were great musicians based on them performing their own songs. If Ringo could play like Philip Simons or Neil Pert, I'd be very surprised. Same with the others. They played their own music like no others, but does that make them better than average?

This question raises the interesting point of voice as an instrument. The Beatles wrote songs, not instrumentals. Their mastery of instruments was good, as many answers testified, but their mastery of the voice as instrument is unparalled. Most people perhaps consider voice as a vehicle for words, so lyrics matter. Whereas John indeed values words as part of voice (but not always; compare In my life with I am the walrus), Paul is more interested in the voice’s tone. His lyrics are, thus, often throwaways (but not always; compare She's leaving home with I will). Both, however, make the sound of voice unforgettable, and they are just phenomenal artists in this area. Voice is what makes the Beatles. “Yeah, yeah, yeah”, “Na, na, na, nanana”

No they shouldn't. Sure if you compare a bass player like Paul McCartney to someone like John Entwistle than John would obviously win based on technique. That being said… Paul has the most incredible bass lines of all time. The way in which Paul forethought his lines is still unreachable to this day. Lennon was a superb rhythm guitarist. And Ringo has imprinted his distinct style on rock till it desists.

They weren’t virtuosos but they were incredibly creative. Most of the early songs were done quickly, with George and Ringo having to figure out their parts quickly after hearing the song for the first time in the studio. Take just one song for an example “All my loving”. Listen to the great McCartney melody and vocal supported by John driving triplets on rhythm guitar, George’s out of left field solo, McCartney’s rolling bass line and Ringo whacking those skins. Amazing

I believe even the Beatles did not feel that they were virtuoso musicians, but instead viewed themselves as average musicians. But ‘being good musicians’ was not their claim to fame. It was their music writing ability, and initially the vocal harmonies that made them so popular. Oh, and the girls thought they were kind of cute. Reminds me of the Wicked song “Popular”…

I played professionally for over 10 years. Most musicians (self included) think of the Beatles as “above-average” in musicianship but off the charts in innovative creativity. They “led” and changed the music world.

I have been involved in the music industry for most of my life. I have been a member of many ‘club bands’ and was a studio musician with Warner Music in the late 60s-early 70s. I have a very reverent feeling toward the Beatles. They were ground breakers and innovators and because of their popularity they had a tremendous influence on music. A very positive influence. Man for man, they weren’t the best guitarists, bassists and drummer on the planet but they were instrumental in ‘opening the door’ for so many that were. I, for one, am grateful that the Beatles showed up in the music scene when they did. They have earned my gratitude and the gratitude of so many that took their unique lead. Thank you John, Paul, George and Ringo…well done.

Their strength is composition more than performance. As performers, I draw a distinction between art and craft. Is an Olympic gymnast a better dancer than Fred Astair? It depends on what aspect of dance you consider more important: the art, or the craft? It's subjective. Personally, I find Fred Astair's contribution to be rarer and more moving than those of gymnastic competitors. And personally, though I like listening to Eddie Van Halen, I still generally get more pleasure from listening to the Beatles. They tap the emotions without trying to show off their skill. I find that kind of success to be rarer than success at speed or complexity.

One of my grandmothers was a gifted musician (and one grandfather was a violin maker). That grandmother played in some of the big band-type groups in the 1940s. My grandmother’s first hearing of the Beatles made her cringe. But, perhaps respecting my youthful enthusiasm and lack of musical knowledge, all she said was that they were off key and could not carry a tune. I can’t imagine what she would have thought of rap. I’m reasonably sure she would not have considered it music at all (with perhaps some exceptions).

Well, they were pop musicians. Virtuosity was not called for. They were great songwriters; they had 6 songs in the Billboard top ten simultaneously in 1967 or 68 I'm not sure. That has never been achieved by anyone else since. It is just astonishing feat. I have many friends who like myself are jazz musicians. Some of these are a little too quick to rubbish pop music. To them I say “Try to write one song that even gets near the point charts. Now try to get one in the top 10. Now try for 6 at the same time.

As a musician and songwriter I can say they were the best as what they did…they were a NWO of rock/pop. And some of the songwriting was exceptional. A song like She's Leaving Home is genius. Am I a Beatles addic? Not in the least. But as a singer songwriter I will give credit where due. And they earned respect from me.

The Beatles, for the most part, were not gifted musicians. They were gifted writers though and they had stage presence and charisma. The Beatles prove a point; music is not about being a virtuoso, it’s about the feelings that are communicated. Bob Dylan or Mick Jagger are not great singers but widely popular regardless.

Sure, they were average players. But they had something a lot of players don’t have. The understood the art of playing a song. Whatever your instrument, this is what makes a good musician. Play what’s right for a song.

VIRTUOSITY was the key word when describing THE WHO. Marketing was a powerful weapon for The Beatles, but they were not as good at creativity. Entwhistle was the best when we speak about musical education and he made orchestral arrangements for the top proyects, Moon one of the top drum set players but Townshend was the creative genius, indeed. THE WHO created the concept of Opera Rock after Townie listened to The Pretty Things’ “HMS Sorrow” and then “A Quick One” (While He’s Away) came and later the conceptual album was developed in “The Who Sell Out”. Synthesizers were used in “Baba O’Reilly” in “Who Came First”. So, the real conceptual musical evolution was made and executed by THE WHO. “Sergeant Pepper” came a lot later, by the way.

You have to judge them as a group not as individuals. They achieved a perfect fusion of their individual talents, their greatness was in the their harmony. Surely music is to be heard…and the whole world stopped what they were doing and listened...that’s greatness. With the basic equipment they had, I can’t see how they could have achieved more.

None of the Beatles were flashy, virtuosic players—but they were all good players, and extremely musical thinkers. That’s the opposite of someone who has incredible chops on their instrument, but has no musical instinct or creativity.
